    "Furthermore, as we saw in the discussion of intersectionality [36], treating \"race\" and \"gender\" as separate constructs further obscures some identities by implying, for example, that all women share a collective experience.A critical approach to computational social science wouldn't argue that such racial or gender classification is never appropriate but rather would encourage researchers to be continuously critical of the role power plays in such analysis.",
